%[text] # **posField Desorption Map**
%[text] **Creation of field desorption map images and movies**
%[text] The field desorption map can be very informative since it highlights areas of variation in needed fields for the evaporation of matter and therefore comprises information such as the relative location of grain boundaries, differing phases, pole figures, and others. For the construction of a field desorption map, the x- and y-coordinates of the hit events on the detector are needed. Therefore, instead of the often used \*.pos file, for example an \*.epos file needs to be loaded. This is also possible with the function *posToTable*.
%[text] If the user wants to display only hits assigned to specific species, the mass spectrum needs to be ranged and the epos file allocated. The latter works exactly as the allocating for the pos file 
%[text] (epos = posAllocateRange(epos,rangesExtractFromMassSpec(spec),'decompose');)
%[text] If the user does not want to distinguish between certain species, no mass spectrum needs to be ranged and no allocation needs to be performed (see last section of this workflow).
%[text] NOTE: The user has to select (\*.epos) as displayed data type in the dialog box when loading a new file.
epos = posToTable; % loading of an *.epos file %[output:93658938] %[output:54e20342]
  %[control:button:6d8b]{"position":[1,2]}
%[text] 
%%
%[text] ## **Creation of bin vectors**
%[text] In a further step, the detector plane is divided into bins. As distance variable (*dist*) the x- and y-coordinates of the detector are used. The *bin* variable must contain the bin width for both binning directions. It determines the resolution of the resulting field desorption map. Different bin widths are possible.
dist = [pos.detx, pos.dety]; % determination of the distance variables to be binned
bin = [0.07 0.07]; % bin width in x and y direction %[control:editfield:32ee]{"position":[8,17]}
mode = 'distance'; % 'distance' is the only possible mode in 2D and 3D
[binCenters, binEdges] = binVectorsFromDistance(dist,bin,mode); % creates bin centers and bin edges of the voxels
clearvars bin mode
  %[control:button:46b0]{"position":[1,2]}
%[text] 
%%
%[text] ## Voxelisation of the data set
%[text] In the next step, the voxelisation will be performed based on the bin edges. Each 'voxel' represents in 2D actually a pixel (*pix*).
%[text] The *startIdx* and *endIdx* values define the selection of ion hit indices the user wants to contribute to the creation of the cell array *pix*.
startIdx = 1; % start hit index  %[control:editfield:2e78]{"position":[12,13]}
endIdx = height(pos); % end hit index, must be greater than startIdx %[control:editfield:5440]{"position":[10,21]}
pix = posNdBin(pos(startIdx:endIdx,:),dist(startIdx:endIdx,:),binEdges); % creates a cell array of various epos subsets, representing the voxelisation of the epos variable
  %[control:button:5810]{"position":[1,2]}
%%
%[text] ## Creation of an anonymous function
%[text] In the next step, a so-called 'anonymous function' will be defined. This means that a function handle will be created, here it is called *concentrationKernel*. By doing so, in a subsequent step the here defined function can be applied on many elements of a cell array.
%[text] As input, the detector efficiency is needed. For example, in case of the LEAP 4000X HR, this value is 0.37 or 37 %, respectively.
%[text] The inputs *excludeListConc* and *volumeName* are optional:
detEff = 82; % detector efficiency, input as decimal or percentage figure possible %[control:editfield:88e3]{"position":[10,12]}
excludeListConc = {'unranged', 'Ga'}; % list of ions that shall not be considered for the concentration calculation, unranged atoms appear as 'unranged', optional %[control:editfield:251b]{"position":[19,37]}
volumeName = '3526'; % name of the volumes, parsed as character array, optional %[control:editfield:9119]{"position":[14,20]}
concentrationKernel = @(epos) posCalculateConcentrationSimple(epos,detEff,excludeListConc,volumeName);
  %[control:button:2891]{"position":[1,2]}
%[text] ## 
%%
%[text] ## Calculation of the concentrations
%[text] In the following section, the concentration (and also count and variance) for all not excluded species are calculated for each pixel. This is done with MATLAB's function *cellfun*. This command applies the function *func* to the contents of each cell of the cell array *cell*.
%[text] NOTE: The bin size (specified in the first section) has a huge impact on the computing time of this command. Bin sizes of 1 to 2 nm seem rather reasonable.
func = concentrationKernel; % specification of the function to be applied on cell array
cell = pix; % specification of cell array
conc = cellfun(func,cell,'UniformOutput',false); % calculation of concentration for each cell/pixel %[output:1d3a1388]
  %[control:button:9c37]{"position":[1,2]}
%%
%[text] In order to create a heat map for a specific species, the wanted species must be defined.
wantedSpecies = cellfun(@(epos) epos.Al(epos.format == 'concentration'),conc); %[control:editfield:3036]{"position":[38,40]}
figure; %[output:3fb928dc]
imageFDM = imagesc(binCenters{1},binCenters{2},wantedSpecies); % creates image of the concentration map of the specified species %[output:3fb928dc]
axis equal; %[output:3fb928dc]
  %[control:button:3ce4]{"position":[1,2]}
%[text] 
%%
%[text] ## **Creation of field desorption map movie**
%[text] With the creation of a field desorption map movie, the user can visualise the 'movement' of grain boundaries and other features during the measurement. 
%[text] The inputs *frames*, *sample*, *RES*, and *fileName* are optional. The input *frames* defines the number of created field desoprtion map frames, which assemble the movie. Since the playing speed is set to 30 frames per second, this input affects the resulting movie length (the movie is created by stacking separate images). *sample* specifies the number of ions for each field desorption map frame. It is limited by the resolution of the field desorption map. The input *RES* represents the resolution, hence the number of pixels both in x and y direction. *fileName* defines the name of the movie file with an .avi suffix. It will be saved in the current folder.
%[text] NOTE: In the movie all ion hits (of all species) are taken into account.
frames =  300; % number of frames of the movie %[control:editfield:175d]{"position":[11,14]}
sample = 10000; % specification of sample size for each image %[control:editfield:5d39]{"position":[10,15]}
RES = 100; % resolution of the field desorption map (RES x RES), must be bigger than 1 %[control:editfield:38ef]{"position":[7,10]}
fileName = "5915"; % definition of the file name, file will be saved in current folder %[control:editfield:4a7d]{"position":[12,18]}
movieFDM = movieCreateFieldDesorptionMap(epos.detx,epos.dety,frames,sample,RES,fileName);
  %[control:button:4390]{"position":[1,2]}
%%
%[text] ## Creation of a FDM with only an epos file
%[text] If the user wants to create a field desorption map only with an epos file, only the section with the creation of bin vectors needs to be executed beforehand.
%[text] With the MATLAB function *hist3*, a 3D histogram can be created. By specifying the indices of the detected hits (with the start value *'from'* and the end value *'to'*), the user can vary the number of hits contributing to the histogram and also in a way the time period of the measurement (by shifting the values). 
%[text] NOTE: The starting value must be smaller than the end value. Furthermore, the axes scaling changes with changing bin width and therefore, the units are arbitrary.
from = 1; % definition of the start index of detected ion %[control:editfield:18b7]{"position":[8,9]}
to = 16854314; % definition of the end index of detected ion, must be bigger than 'from' value %[control:editfield:79f4]{"position":[6,14]}
FDM = hist3([epos.detx(from:to),epos.dety(from:to)],binCenters); % creates array of the 3D histogram
imageFDM = imagesc(FDM); axis equal; % creates image of the field desorption map %[output:3d358e0a]
clearvars from to 
  %[control:button:304a]{"position":[1,2]}

